metadata.name: Ghostly Solarized #8
metadata.description:
"Ghostly Solarized" is an AI-assisted and PFP-friendly generative digital art collection reflecting on chaos, pixelart and cyberpunk motives.

The idea behind "Ghostly Solarized" is to create a series of artworks influenced by digital and organic shapes and the chaotic nature of the universe. The collection is meant to reflect on the relationship between humanity and technology and how our increasing reliance on technology impacts our lives and our world.

Press [S] to save.

Utilised a fine-tuned Solarized colour theme by Ethan Schoonover, Bj√∂rn Ottosson
 and Zack Voase:
- https://ethanschoonover.com/solarized/
- https://bottosson.github.io/posts/oklab/
- https://meat.io/oksolar

metadata.name: LA BOUGIE üïØ #81
metadata.description:
This work is a collection along the lines of abstract works that I produced during the last year, and this is the first generative project in the form of a collaboration with the artist's friend Arash. This is the beginning of the production of fascinating works that we have been working on for several projects for months. In the background of this piece, there is a combination of Mondrian's known works with his well-known color palette and style, and the compositions try to remember Mondrian's works and create new and different designs. This deconstruction of The style Art movement continued and flourished with his other contemporary artists; Fx Hash's one-year candle combines de Stijl's work with a new pattern that creates new compositions independent of this work.

Unique collection by ArashMp and Chistai for #fxhashturnsone
Happy birthday fx(hash)!

metadata.name: barcode(fxhash) #271
metadata.description:
[UPDATED: There was a bug in the first edition of this token that has been solved in this. All minters of the previous edition, has a reserve of 2]

barcode(fxhash) converts the ascii characters from the transaction hash of the token (fxhash variable) into barcodes for each of 51 characters. It uses Code 39 (https://github.com/graphicore/librebarcode), so it is not case sensitive. Each iteration has from 1 to 8 columns, and from 1 to 8 rows, and the frist N characters of the fxhash are displayed in one of first N positions (first 2 characters are discarted). If the number of characters is greater than 49 (length of fxhash discarting 'oo'), the boxes will continue to be filled, returning from the third character of fxhash.

Features generated by fxrand() random function:

-num_chars: number of characters displayed. from 1 to 64. They are the first N characters of fxhash.
-has_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash'.
-show_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash' and these are all displayed.
-columns: number of columns (1-8).
-rows: number of rows (1-8).
-color_mode: color mode white (light) or black (dark).
-separacio: factor of separation between barcodes (1.1, 1.5 or 2)
-scale_type: scale type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-rotate_type: rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-transparent: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes has a transparent background.
-squares: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes width=height.
-main_shadow: blur value for main shadow.
-exterior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-interior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)


(There are more values generated by fxrand() not shown as Feature)

click to show all fxhash barcodes, wich are displayed.

metadata.name: Sweeping #131
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- Double Click to open a User Interface
- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

---

Made with p5js + webgl by Wouter Missler, 2022.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

share your tokens on social media with #genxyznft

metadata.name: CMYK Decay #50
metadata.description:
Layers of Cyan, Magenta, Yellow & Key (Black) fight for your attention as they slowly decay and disappear.

Decay speed, layer order and transform scale are influenced by random numbers. Extreme transformations are less common.

metadata.name: Encapsulated #299
metadata.description:
Have you ever felt fear? Have you ever felt tired? Have you ever felt trapped and watched? The bars of the big cities are supposed to bring us protection, but in the end, we are encapsulated in this big prison.

This project was made thinking about that feeling of prison ourselves and will participate in the #fxhashturnsone event. 

Fully made with p5.js and p5.grain

metadata.name: Polar Grid #311
metadata.description:
Polar Grid is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

This is a study of color, motion, and composition, and an homage to cinema as an artform. Colorful shapes overlap and pulse in a ever repeating dance. An abstracted movie experience. Each color palette in the series (except one) is inspired by a different film director (if you want a real challenge, see how many you can guess without looking at the feature names).

The palettes were extracted from movie stills or movie posters and fine tuned by hand. As often, I have to thank independent tool makers for their indirect help. My gratitude goes to David Aerne for FarbV√©lo and Fabrizio Bianchi for Coolors.

The code for Polar Grid is based on early iterations of what ultimately became my carat series. Both projects come from the same fascination for color as a system, even though I used a different approach here. You could call this a carat prequel.

The animation is done using a technique called polar noise. This makes it so the motion of all elements ends up repeating in the same amount of time. This is useful for generating motion that loops perfectly while still appearing organic. In this particular case, the animation repeats every œÄ √ó 100 seconds.

A challenge in building any generative system is to find the right balance between coherence and variety. I designed the system with the large edition size in mind. During development I generated hundreds of iterations and tweaked my code to make sure that every iteration is truly unique and fits the overall aesthetic of the collection.

I truly hope you will enjoy your own little abstract movie.

‚Äî Rapha√´l de Courville


Released: July 6th 2022

Medium: p5.js, html canvas, css

Reference: sk220621


**About the artist**

Rapha√´l de Courville is a generative artist, streamer, and educator. His artistic work is an exploration of generative systems, patterns, interactivity, and time. Born in Paris, he lives and works in Berlin.
